      "content": "When assessing Mr. Sterling for potential drug-seeking behavior or psychological influence on his pain perception, pay attention to his appearance, demeanor, and responses. Signs such as overly attentive or ingratiating behavior, purchasing of pain medication not covered by insurance, pressing as pain substantially impairs his normal function, or lack of follow-up after evaluations without a clear reason might indicate a risk of drug-seeking.\n\nFurthermore, observe how he handles questions about his pain, his adherence to previously prescribed treatment plans, and any changes in his coping mechanisms since the onset of his symptoms. It's essential to approach each patient with empathy and professionalism while maintaining a valid and thorough assessment process. Communicate the importance of honesty in clinical evaluations to build trust and encourage truthful responses. If there is ever doubt, consider involving a psychologist for a more nuanced assessment of his condition and possible psychological factors influencing his situation.",
